06092nam a22006015i 9780822392507DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223925077 a10.1515/97808223925072doi  a(DE-B1597)554383  a(OCoLC)609924583  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aQB32b.H43 2010 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a520.9/03422204aThe Heavens on Earth :bObservatories and Astronomy in Nineteenth-Century Science and Culture /cDavid Aubin, Charlotte Bigg, E. Roy Weintraub, Barbara Herrnstein Smith, H. Otto Sibum. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (398 p.) :b62 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScience and Cultural Theory00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Observatory Techniques in Nineteenth-Century Science and Society -- t1. The Astronomical Capital of the World: Pulkovo Observatory in the Russia of Tsar Nicholas I -- t2. The Jesuit on the Roof: Observatory Sciences, Metaphysics, and Nation Building -- t3. Eclipse Politics in France and Thailand, 1868 -- t4. Keeping the Books at Paramatta Observatory -- t5. Training Seafarers in Astronomy: Methods, Naval Schools, and Naval Observatories in Eighteenth- and Nineteenth- Century France -- t6. Astronomy as Military Science: The Case of Sweden, ca. 1800-1850 -- t7. Geodesy and Map Making in France and Algeria: Between Army Officers and Observatory Scientists -- t8. Michelson and the Observatory: Physics and the Astronomical Community in Late-Nineteenth-Century America -- t9. Even the Tools Will Be Free: Humboldt's Romantic Technologies -- t10. "I thought this might be of interest . . .": The Observatory as Public Enterprise -- t11. Staging the Heavens: Astrophysics and Popular Astronomy in the Late Nineteenth Century -- t12. The Berlin Urania, Humboldtian Cosmology, and the Public -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Heavens on Earth explores the place of the observatory in nineteenth-century science and culture. Astronomy was a core pursuit for observatories, but usually not the only one. It belonged to a larger group of "observatory sciences" that also included geodesy, meteorology, geomagnetism, and even parts of physics and statistics. These pursuits coexisted in the nineteenth-century observatory; this collection surveys them as a coherent whole. Broadening the focus beyond the solitary astronomer at his telescope, it illuminates the observatory's importance to technological, military, political, and colonial undertakings, as well as in advancing and popularizing the mathematical, physical, and cosmological sciences.The contributors examine "observatory techniques" developed and used not only in connection with observatories but also by instrument makers in their workshops, navy officers on ships, civil engineers in the field, and many others. These techniques included the calibration and coordination of precision instruments for making observations and taking measurements; methods of data acquisition and tabulation; and the production of maps, drawings, and photographs, as well as numerical, textual, and visual representations of the heavens and the earth. They also encompassed the social management of personnel within observatories, the coordination of international scientific collaborations, and interactions with dignitaries and the public. The state observatory occupied a particularly privileged place in the life of the city. With their imposing architecture and ancient traditions, state observatories served representative purposes for their patrons, whether as symbols of a monarch's enlightened power, a nation's industrial and scientific excellence, or republican progressive values. Focusing on observatory techniques in settings from Berlin, London, Paris, and Rome to Australia, Russia, Thailand, and the United States, The Heavens on Earth is a major contribution to the history of science.Contributors: David Aubin, Charlotte Bigg, Guy Boistel, Theresa Levitt, Massimo Mazzotti, Ole Molvig, Simon Schaffer, Martina Schiavon , H. Otto Sibum, Richard Staley, John Tresch, Simon Werrett, Sven Widmalm  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAstronomyxHistoryy19th century. 0aNineteenth century. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh1 aAubin, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBigg, Charlotte, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSibum, H. Otto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Barbara Herrnstein, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeintraub, E. Roy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392507zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392507.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles